message.content:
To align a row of `div` elements to the right using Flexbox in CSS, you can use the `justify-content` property with the value `flex-end`. Here's an example:

HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Flexbox Right Align Example</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="flex-row">
      <div class="item">Item 1</div>
      <div class="item">Item 2</div>
      <div class="item">Item 3</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
```

CSS (styles.css):
```css
body {
  margin: 0;
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

.container {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 800px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: 20px;
}

.flex-row {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end; /* Aligns the items to the right */
}

.item {
  margin: 10px;
  padding: 15px;
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
  border-radius: 5px;
  text-align: center;
}
```

In this example, the `.flex-row` container uses Flexbox with `display: flex;`. The `justify-content: flex-end;` property aligns all child elements (divs with class `item`) to the right side of the container. Each item has some padding and a light gray background for better visibility.

By opening this HTML file in a browser, you will see three items aligned to the right side of the `.flex-row` container.
